insight</reviewer><date>20111023T214936Z</date></review>\n\n  </reviews>\n </evidence>'),('$VAR1 = [\n          bless( {\n                   \'URL\' => \'http://www.greenamerica.org/programs/responsibleshopper/company.cfm?id=457\',\n                   \'SourceText\' => \'Green America: Company ID 457\'\n                 }, \'Com::elle::bLeaf::EvidenceGenerator::NewsSource\' ),\n          \'A recent deal with Standard Renewable Energy is resulting in the implementation of solar energy systems in 75 Chipotle restaurants\'\n        ];\n',' <evidence>\n  <title>A recent deal with Standard Renewable Energy is resulting in the implementation of solar energy systems in 75 Chipotle restaurants</title>\n  <description>\n    A recent deal with Standard Renewable Energy is resulting in the implementation of solar energy systems in 75 Chipotle restaurants. Installations have already started in Denver, the chain\'s home base, but progress has also been made in Austin, Dallas and San Antonio. In total, the panels will produce 500 kilowatt-hours of electricity, making the chain the largest direct producer of solar energy in the restaurant industry. The panels are also expected to reduce carbon dioxide emissions by 41 million pounds over their lifetime. This deal is not Chipotle\'s first demonstration of its commitment to the environment as it was the first restaurant ever to receive Platinum-level LEED certification for its Gurnee, Illinois location. Chipotle also has other LEED-certifeid locations but all of its new restaurants incorporate environmentally-friendly materials such as low-VOC paints, recycled drywall and regulated interior lighting based on the amount of available sunlight. Chipotle also incorporates sustainability into its food by choosing to use more organic meat and dairy products in addition to loaclly grown produce.\r\n\r\n\r\n75 Chipotle restaurants will soon get solar panels on their roof. This will help the company save money and reduce carbon dioxide emissions by 41 million pounds over the panels\' lifetimes. Chipotle was also the first restaurant to ever receive LEED certify. \n\n  </description>\n  <categories>\n    <category>\n      <category-name>Environment</category-name>\n    </category>\n  </categories>\n  <source>\n    <link><link-text>Green America: Company ID 457</link-text><url>http://www.greenamerica.org/programs/responsibleshopper/company.cfm?id=457</url><date>20111024164511</date></link>\n  </source>\n  <links>\n    <link><link-text>Cooler Planet</link-text><url>http://solar.coolerplanet.com/News/10220901-chipotle-goes-with-solar-panels.aspx</url><date></date></link>\n  </links>\n  <companies>\n   <company>\n      <normalized></normalized>\n      <tagged>Chipotle</tagged>\n      <address></address>\n      <GCPs></GCPs>\n    </company>\n   <company>\n      <normalized></normalized>\n      <tagged>Standard Renewable Energy</tagged>\n      <address></address>\n      <GCPs></GCPs>\n    </company>\n  </companies>\n  <reviews>\n        <review><reviewer>insight</reviewer><date>20111023T215149Z</date></review>\n\n  </reviews>\n </evidence>'),('$VAR1 = [\n          bless( {\n                   \'URL\' => \'http://www.greenamerica.org/programs/responsibleshopper/company.cfm?id=180\',\n                   \'SourceText\' => \'Green America: Company ID 180\'\n                 }, \'Com::elle::bLeaf::EvidenceGenerator::NewsSource\' ),\n          \'The Ethical Trading Action Group (ETAG), in association with Maquila Solidarity Network (MSN) and AccountAbility, released a repor\'\n        ];\n',' <evidence>\n  <title>The Ethical Trading Action Group (ETAG), in association with Maquila Solidarity Network (MSN) and AccountAbility, released a repor</title>\n  <description>\n    The Ethical Trading Action Group (ETAG), in association with Maquila Solidarity Network (MSN) and AccountAbility, released a report entitled &quot;Transparency Report Card 2006,&quot; evaluating and comparing 31 apparel retailers and brands in their