rmalized>\n      <tagged>Dominion</tagged>\n      <address></address>\n      <GCPs></GCPs>\n    </company>\n  </companies>\n  <reviews>\n        <review><reviewer>insight</reviewer><date>20111024T004200Z</date></review>\n\n  </reviews>\n </evidence>'),('$VAR1 = [\n          bless( {\n                   \'URL\' => \'http://www.greenamerica.org/programs/responsibleshopper/company.cfm?id=345\',\n                   \'SourceText\' => \'Green America: Company ID 345\'\n                 }, \'Com::elle::bLeaf::EvidenceGenerator::NewsSource\' ),\n          \'Time Warner subsidiary news station NY1 has come under fire for refusing to arrange a debate between Senator Hillary Clinton and D\'\n        ];\n',' <evidence>\n  <title>Time Warner subsidiary news station NY1 has come under fire for refusing to arrange a debate between Senator Hillary Clinton and D</title>\n  <description>\n    Time Warner subsidiary news station NY1 has come under fire for refusing to arrange a debate between Senator Hillary Clinton and Democratic challenger Jonathan Tasini during the New York Senate race in 2006. The station rejected a debate on the grounds that Tasini has not spent enough money on the race.  In order to appear on the station, NY1 requires that candidates poll at least 5 percent and have spent or raised $500,000. Tasini was polling at 13 percent but his campaign had only raised $150,000.  Democracy Now! invited NY1 to respond to this criticism but the station declined. Edward Pachetti, public relations manager for NY1, sent the following statement to Democracy Now! outlining their position: \r\n&lt;p&gt;“NY1 News is producing the most ambitious series of political debates and town hall meetings this election season. As part of the staging of these events, NY1 established criteria to identify which candidates would be invited to participate in these events. The criteria are that a candidate must poll at least five percent (including margin of error) in a recognized independent poll and would need to have spent and/or raised $500,000. All candidates who have met these criteria have been invited to participate.” \n\n  </description>\n  <categories>\n    <category>\n      <category-name>Politics</category-name>\n    </category>\n  </categories>\n  <source>\n    <link><link-text>Green America: Company ID 345</link-text><url>http://www.greenamerica.org/programs/responsibleshopper/company.cfm?id=345</url><date>20111024164705</date></link>\n  </source>\n  <links>\n    <link><link-text>Democracy Now!</link-text><url>http://www.democracynow.org</url><date></date></link>\n  </links>\n  <companies>\n   <company>\n      <normalized>Time Warner Cable</normalized>\n      <tagged>Time Warner</tagged>\n      <address>MN\n9705 Data Park\n55343-9119 \nMinnetonka\nUnited States</address>\n      <GCPs><GCP>083633600</GCP></GCPs>\n    </company>\n   <company>\n      <normalized>Time Warner Interactive Group</normalized>\n      <tagged>Time Warner</tagged>\n      <address>NY\n1 Time Warner Center\n10019 \nNew York\nUnited States</address>\n      <GCPs><GCP>0099171</GCP></GCPs>\n    </company>\n  </companies>\n  <reviews>\n        <review><reviewer>insight</reviewer><date>20111024T004312Z</date></review>\n\n  </reviews>\n </evidence>'),('$VAR1 = [\n          bless( {\n                   \'URL\' => \'http://www.greenamerica.org/programs/responsibleshopper/company.cfm?id=449\',\n                   \'SourceText\' => \'Green America: Company ID 449\'\n                 }, \'Com::elle::bLeaf::EvidenceGenerator::NewsSource\' ),\n          \'Darden Restaurants is launching a sustainable restaurant design initiative, requiring that all new restaurants be built to the US \'\n        ];\n',' <evidence>\n  <title>Darden Restaurants is launching a sustainable restaurant design initiative, requiring that all new restaurants be built to the US </title>\n  <description>\n    Darden Restaurants is launching a sustainable restaurant design initiative, requiring that all new restaurants be built to the US Green Building Council’s LEED standards and all restaurant remodels follow the LEED Rating Systems when feasible. The initiative is launching with eight restaurants, either built or still in the process of being built, to receive LEED certification. Measures taken to achieve LEED status included using recycled building materials, increase the use of windows to provide natural lighting, use low flow plumbing and Energy Star rated appliances in the kitchen. \n\n  </description>\n  <categories>\n    <category>\n      <category-name>Environment</category-name>\n    </category>\n  </categories>\n  <source>\n    <link><link-text>Green America: Company ID 449</link-text><url>http://www.greenamerica.org/programs/responsibleshopper/company.cfm?id=449</url><date>20111024164705</date></link>\n  </source>\n  <links>\n    <link><link-text>Forbes</link-text><url>http://http://www.forbes.com/2010/02/24/red-lobster-restaurants-technology-ecotech-darden.html </url><date></date></link><link><link-text></link-text><url>http://</url><date></date></link>\n  </links>\n  <companies>\n   <company>\n      <normalized></normalized>\n      <tagged>Darden Restaurants</tagged>\n      <address></address>\n      <GCPs></GCPs>\n    </company>\n  </companies>\n  <reviews>\n        <review><reviewer>insight</reviewer><date>20111024T004325Z</date></review>\n\n  </reviews>\n </evidence>'),('$VAR1 = [\n          bless( {\n                   \'URL\' => \'http://www.greenamerica.org/programs/responsibleshopper/company.cfm?id=245\',\n                   \'SourceText\' => \'Green America: Company ID 245\'\n                 }, \'Com::elle::bLeaf::EvidenceGenerator::NewsSource\' ),\n          \'In April 2003, a federal court on the Pacific Island of Saipan approved a $20 million settlement on a class action lawsuit filed a\'\n        ];\n',' <evidence>\n  <title>In April 2003, a federal court on the Pacific Island of Saipan approved a $20 million settlement on a class action lawsuit filed a</title>\n  <description>\n    In April 2003, a federal court on the Pacific Island of Saipan approved a $20 million settlement on a class action lawsuit filed against JCPenney and 25 other U.S. retailers. The lawsuit charged that the companies contracted sweatshop labor on Saipan, a U.S. Commonwealth, and should be held accountable for worker treatment and conditions in foreign-owned factories operating on U.S. soil. According to the complaint, the more than 30,000 garment workers involved regularly worked 12-hour days, seven days a week, often times &quot;off the clock&quot; without receiving any pay or overtime. The lawsuit also accused JCPenney and the other companies of operating a &quot;racketeering conspiracy&quot; through which workers, who are mostly young women, sign contracts waiving their basic human rights and pay recruitment fees of up to $10,000 to secure sweatshop jobs. By agreeing to the terms of the settlement, the companies admitted no wrongdoing. \n\n  </description>\n  <categories>\n    <category>\n      <category-name>Business Practices | Workers Rights</category-name>\n    </category>\n  </categories>\n  <source>\n    <link><link-text>Green America: Company ID 245</link-text><url>http://www.greenamerica.org/programs/responsibleshopper/company.cfm?id=245</url><date>20111024164706</date></link>\n  </source>\n  <links>\n    <link><link-text>Clean Clothes Campaign</link-text><url>http://www.cleanclothes.org/legal/04-01-08.htm</url><date></date></link>\n  </links>\n  <companies>\n   <company>\n      <normalized></normalized>\n      <tagged>JCPenney</tagged>\n      <address></address>\n      <GCPs></GCPs>\n    </company>\n  </companies>\n  <reviews>\n        <review><reviewer>insight</reviewer><date>20111024T004410Z</date></review>\n\n  </reviews>\n </evidence>');
